dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-IMPL-20260527T140358Z.log:32:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NryMDnUcQK5meBg9yCVbV1","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\ttitle: 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\n3\tdate: 2026-05-27\n4\ttarget_release: 0.7.0\n5\tdesc: Pack 1 schema-migration + ingest double-write decisions for\n6\t  the binary-quantization data-encoding change locked by\n7\t  ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md.\n8\tblast_radius: src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs (schema +\n9\t  writer); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs\n10\t  (existing fixture continuity); dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md\n11\t  (implements its Pack 1 section).\n12\tstatus: draft fix-3 (consumed by Pack 1 implementation)\n13\t---\n14\t\n15\t# 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\n16\t\n17\tThis memo resolves the open design questions called out in\n18\t`dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-PERF-VECTOR-QUANT-HANDOFF.md` § \"Pack 1\"\n19\tand § \"Open items the implementing agent should escalate to HITL\"\n20\tso that Pack 1 implementation can land mechanically. Pairs with\n21\tADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md (which records the *what*); this\n22\tmemo records the *exact shape*.\n23\t\n24\tScope: Pack 1 only — schema migration + writer double-write. No\n25\treader changes. The Pack 2 query rewrite is out of scope for this\n26\tmemo and is owned by a separate design pass when Pack 2 starts.\n27\t\n28\t## D1 — Sibling column vs. sibling table\n29\t\n30\t**Decision: sibling column on `vector_default`.**\n31\t\n32\tThe migrated declaration is:\n33\t\n34\t```\n35\tCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n36\t  embedding float[<dim>],\n37\t  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n38\t  source_type TEXT partition key,\n39\t  kind TEXT,\n40\t  created_at INTEGER\n41\t);\n42\t```\n43\t\n44\t(`<dim>` = 768 for the current default profile; the existing\n45\t`ensure_vector_partition` builds the dimension from\n46\t`load_default_profile` at `lib.rs:3278-3283`.)\n47\t\n48\t- Alternatives weighed: sibling table `vector_default_bin` (one\n49\t  extra join on every read; fan-out cost on the Pack 2 reader; two\n50\t  inserts per row instead of one; two DELETE sites in every\n51\t  excise / rebuild path — `lib.rs:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`).\n52\t- Citation: the sqlite-vec binary-quant guide demonstrates the\n53\t  exact mixed-flavour declaration\n54\t  `create virtual table vec_movies using vec0(synopsis_embedding\n55\t  float[768], synopsis_embedding_coarse bit[768])`\n56\t  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html);\n57\t  confirmed empirically by WebFetch on 2026-05-27 against the\n58\t  same page.\n59\t\n60\tThe sibling-column shape is the default in the handoff\n61\t(§ 1.1) and in the ADR (§ 2 / Pack 1.1). The sibling-table\n62\tfallback remains documented in both as a recovery path **only if**\n63\tthe 16-metadata-column cap is exceeded (see D2) — that is not the\n64\tcase for Pack 1.\n65\t\n66\t## D2 — Metadata column inventory (vec0 16-col cap)\n67\t\n68\tvec0 caps metadata columns at 16 and partition keys at 4\n69\t(`dev/notes/0.7.0-vector-cost-research.md:70-71`). The Pack 1\n70\tschema lands the minimum-viable set with headroom for the\n71\treal-workload extension already foreseen by the ADR and the\n72\tHITL doc.\n73\t\n74\tPack 1 column inventory on `vector_default`:\n75\t\n76\t| # | Column            | Type           | Role                  | Source                                                         |\n77\t|---|-------------------|----------------|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|\n78\t| 0 | `rowid`           | INTEGER        | (implicit pk)         | `cursor` (existing — `lib.rs:2845-2851`).                      |\n79\t| 1 | `embedding`       | `float[<dim>]` | vector                | existing — `vec_quantize_binary` input + Pack 2 rerank.        |\n80\t| 2 | `embedding_bin`   | `bit[<dim>]`   | quantized vector      | `vec_quantize_binary(embedding)` at write time.                |\n81\t| 3 | `source_type`     | `TEXT`         | **partition key**     | derived from `kind` per D3.                                    |\n82\t| 4 | `kind`            | `TEXT`         | metadata col          | existing `ProjectionOutcome::Success.kind` (`lib.rs:2841`).    |\n83\t| 5 | `created_at`      | `INTEGER`     | metadata col          | UNIX seconds at write time (mirrors `excised_at` pattern at `lib.rs:2206`). |\n84\t\n85\tHeadroom: **11 free metadata column slots + 3 free partition-key\n86\tslots** after Pack 1.\n87\t\n88\tDeferred to Pack 2 / 0.7.1 (NOT landed in Pack 1):\n89\t\n90\t- `tags`, `project_mentions` — named in the handoff § 1.1 but not\n91\t  populated by today's writer; the chunk record carries no such\n92\t  field. Wiring requires upstream code changes that are out of\n93\t  scope for the Pack 1 schema-only slice. Headroom preserved.\n94\t- Any per-source metadata (sender, doc URL, etc.) — corpus-card\n95\t  work; lives outside Pack 1.\n96\t\n97\tRationale for landing `created_at` now: it is the one non-\n98\tcontroversial metadata field with a deterministic write-time\n99\tsource (clock at insert), it is cheap to add to the migration,\n100\tand the alternative (a second migration in 0.7.1 to add it) costs\n101\tanother ~64 s rebuild of the 1 M-row corpus. Adds zero\n102\timplementation risk because the writer site already calls\n103\t`SystemTime::now()` for the excise-audit path (`lib.rs:2206`).\n104\t\n105\t## D3 — `kind` -> `source_type` mapping\n106\t\n107\tThe locked `source_type` vocabulary is\n108\t{`email`, `article`, `paper`, `meeting`, `note`, `todo`}\n109\t(`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137`; cardinality\n110\t\"~6\" in the ADR § 2).\n111\t\n112\tThe current writer at `commit_projection_outcomes`\n113\t(`lib.rs:2841`) receives `kind: String` from\n114\t`ProjectionOutcome::Success`. The only kind exercised by tests\n115\ttoday is `\"doc\"` (AC-013 fixture seed at\n116\t`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), a synthetic name introduced for the\n117\tperformance fixture and **not** in the locked source_type\n118\tvocabulary.\n119\t\n120\t**Decision: the locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary holds\n121\tunchanged. The synthetic test fixture kind `\"doc\"` is coerced\n122\tat the writer to `source_type = \"article\"`; the vocabulary is\n123\tnot extended.** No HITL re-open required — the lock at\n124\t`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` is honored\n125\texactly.\n126\t\n127\tMapping table (Pack 1, deterministic, total):\n128\t\n129\t| Incoming `kind` value | Resolved `source_type` |\n130\t|-----------------------|------------------------|\n131\t| `\"email\"`             | `email`                |\n132\t| `\"article\"`           | `article`              |\n133\t| `\"paper\"`             | `paper`                |\n134\t| `\"meeting\"`           | `meeting`              |\n135\t| `\"note\"`              | `note`                 |\n136\t| `\"todo\"`              | `todo`                 |\n137\t| `\"doc\"` (synthetic test fixture from `tests/perf_gates.rs:350`) | `article` (coerced) |\n138\t| anything else         | **writer error** — fail the projection outcome (`EngineError::Storage`); do not silently default. |\n139\t\n140\tRationale for the `doc` -> `article` coercion: AC-013 seeds\n141\tsynthetic doc-shaped bodies (long-form text) that are the most\n142\tsemantically aligned with the `article` source within the locked\n143\t6-value set. The coercion (a) preserves the partition_key\n144\tutility for the AC-013 fixture rows (they aggregate under a real\n145\tsource_type bucket the corpus-build work will also populate),\n146\t(b) avoids any test churn — the fixture continues to write\n147\t`kind=\"doc\"`; only the resolved `source_type` differs, (c)\n148\tmatches what `CORPUS-1` (CNN/DailyMail acquisition, commit\n149\t`27ab8df`) will land as the production article source. The\n150\tcoercion is writer-internal; the canonical `kind` value is\n151\tpreserved verbatim in the `kind` metadata column (and in\n152\t`_fathomdb_vector_rows`), so any consumer needing to distinguish\n153\tfixture rows from corpus rows can still do so by reading `kind`.\n154\t\n155\tRejected alternatives:\n156\t\n157\t- \"Add `doc` as a 7th `source_type` value\" — extends the\n158\t  HITL-locked vocabulary without authorization. This was the\n159\t  original draft and is the blocking finding in the codex\n160\t  verdict (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`\n161\t  finding 1).\n162\t- \"Rename the fixture kind from `doc` to one of the 6 locked\n163\t  values\" — touches every test that reads the AC-013 fixture\n164\t  (larger blast radius than a writer-side coercion).\n165\t- \"Leave `source_type` nullable for unmapped kinds\" — loses the\n166\t  partition_key benefit for the AC-013 fixture and breaks the\n167\t  \"partition_key is locked\" guarantee in HITL Q5.\n168\t\n169\tCitation: HITL lock at\n170\t`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` (vocabulary +\n171\t\"supersedes the `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff\").\n172\t\n173\tThe mapping is implemented in a single Rust helper:\n174\t\n175\t```rust\n176\tfn resolve_source_type(kind: &str) -> Result<&'static str, EngineError> {\n177\t    Ok(match kind {\n178\t        \"email\" => \"email\",\n179\t        \"article\" => \"article\",\n180\t        \"paper\" => \"paper\",\n181\t        \"meeting\" => \"meeting\",\n182\t        \"note\" => \"note\",\n183\t        \"todo\" => \"todo\",\n184\t        // Synthetic AC-013 test fixture; coerced to \"article\" so\n185\t        // the 6-value HITL lock holds. See D3 rationale above.\n186\t        \"doc\" => \"article\",\n187\t        _ => return Err(EngineError::Storage),\n188\t    })\n189\t}\n190\t```\n191\t\n192\t(no allocator pressure; returns `&'static str`; used at both\n193\twriter sites in D7.)\n194\t\n195\t## D4 — NOT NULL + migration strategy\n196\t\n197\tvec0 virtual tables in sqlite-vec `=0.1.7` (this repo's pin)\n198\tsupport neither `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (a SQLite-level\n199\trule for virtual tables — https://www.sqlite.org/vtab.html) nor\n200\t`ALTER TABLE ... RENAME` (rename support landed in sqlite-vec\n201\t`v0.1.10-alpha.2`, April 2026, per the sqlite-vec release\n202\thistory). The migration is therefore a `DROP TABLE` + recreate\n203\tunder the same name. Repopulation must be **synchronous and\n204\tin-transaction**, copying the existing f32 blobs verbatim — it\n205\tmust NOT go through the engine's async rebuild driver.\n206\t\n207\t**Decision: land NOT NULL constraints from the start. The\n208\tmigration is a single SQL migration step that (a) stages the\n209\texisting f32 rows + kind into a regular SQL table, (b) drops\n210\tand recreates `vector_default` with the new schema under the\n211\tsame name, (c) repopulates `vector_default` from the staging\n212\ttable with `vec_quantize_binary` evaluated SQL-side at INSERT\n213\tbind, and (d) drops the staging table — all inside the migration\n214\tframework's `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` / `COMMIT` envelope. The writer\n215\tenforces non-nullability from commit zero.**\n216\t\n217\tSchema versioning is owned by the engine's real migration\n218\tframework: `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at\n219\t`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1238`, which is a\n220\tthin re-export of `fathomdb_schema::migrate_with_event_sink`\n221\timplemented at `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:218-271`.\n222\t`apply_one` (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`)\n223\twraps each migration step in `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT`,\n224\tcalling `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)` followed by\n225\t`pragma_update(PRAGMA_USER_VERSION, step_id)`, and rolling back\n226\ton any error. `Migration` itself is `{ step_id: u32, sql:\n227\t&'static str }` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`) — pure SQL,\n228\tno Rust callback hook. The new vec0 schema lands as a new\n229\t`fathomdb_schema::Migration` step appended to the existing\n230\tmigration array passed into `open_with_migrations`\n231\t(`lib.rs:1119-1131`); `migrate_with_event_sink` bumps\n232\t`PRAGMA user_version` on commit and gates re-entry on the same\n233\tsentinel, so re-opens are naturally idempotent. The previously\n234\tproposed `operational_mutations` schema stamp is **not** the\n235\tschema-version owner — that collection is excise audit rows\n236\t(`lib.rs:2217-2221`) — and is dropped from the design.\n237\t\n238\tMigration step (Pack 1) — single SQL blob, executed atomically\n239\tby `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`):\n240\t\n241\t```sql\n242\t-- Step body. Runs inside BEGIN IMMEDIATE ... COMMIT supplied\n243\t-- by apply_one (fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288), which\n244\t-- invokes conn.execute_batch(migration.sql) — i.e. the migration\n245\t-- string is treated as a multi-statement batch (re-verified\n246\t-- against fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:276). Sub-steps below may\n247\t-- therefore be separate SQL statements in the same string.\n248\t--\n249\t-- <dim> is rendered at migration-build time (768 for the default\n250\t-- profile, see ensure_vector_partition at lib.rs:3278-3283).\n251\t-- created_at is filled by strftime('%s','now') evaluated at\n252\t-- INSERT time. Per SQLite's date/time function contract\n253\t-- (https://www.sqlite.org/lang_datefunc.html), built-in date/time\n254\t-- functions return the same value for every row within a single\n255\t-- SQL statement when no varying arguments are passed; the whole\n256\t-- corpus is therefore backfilled with one uniform created_at\n257\t-- value — no Rust-side timestamp rendering, no migration-build-\n258\t-- time substitution.\n259\t\n260\t-- 0. Preflight assertion: abort the migration if any existing\n261\t--    kind is not in the locked source_type vocabulary (incl. the\n262\t--    doc->article coercion in D3). The CHECK constraint on\n263\t--    _vec0_migration_assertion.check_passes fires SQLITE_CONSTRAINT\n264\t--    at INSERT time when check_passes evaluates to 0, which\n265\t--    aborts the migration; apply_one's ROLLBACK undoes the\n266\t--    sentinel-table CREATE alongside it. CHECK constraints on\n267\t--    regular tables are vanilla SQLite (no extension needed):\n268\t--    https://www.sqlite.org/lang_createtable.html#check_constraints\n269\tCREATE TEMP TABLE _vec0_migration_assertion(\n270\t  check_passes INTEGER NOT NULL CHECK(check_passes = 1)\n271\t);\n272\tINSERT INTO _vec0_migration_assertion(check_passes)\n273\tSELECT CASE WHEN EXISTS (\n274\t  SELECT 1 FROM _fathomdb_vector_rows\n275\t  WHERE kind NOT IN ('email','article','paper','meeting','note','todo','doc')\n276\t) THEN 0 ELSE 1 END;\n277\t\n278\t-- 1. Stage existing f32 blobs + kind into a regular SQL table.\n279\t--    _fathomdb_vector_rows.kind is the source of truth for the\n280\t--    existing rows' kind (writer site at lib.rs:2845-2853).\n281\tCREATE TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 (\n282\t  rowid     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n283\t  embedding BLOB NOT NULL,\n284\t  kind      TEXT NOT NULL\n285\t);\n286\tINSERT INTO _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0(rowid, embedding, kind)\n287\tSELECT v.rowid, v.embedding, r.kind\n288\t  FROM vector_default v\n289\t  JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid = v.rowid;\n290\t\n291\t-- 2. Drop the old vec0 table and recreate under the same name.\n292\tDROP TABLE vector_default;\n293\tCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n294\t  embedding float[<dim>],\n295\t  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n296\t  source_type TEXT partition key,\n297\t  kind TEXT,\n298\t  created_at INTEGER\n299\t);\n300\t\n301\t-- 3. Repopulate from staging. vec_quantize_binary runs SQL-side\n302\t--    once per row against the existing f32 blob; source_type is\n303\t--    coerced from kind via the D3 mapping using a CASE\n304\t--    expression. The ELSE branch is 'article' (matching the\n305\t--    D3 doc->article coercion); it is in principle unreachable\n306\t--    because sub-step 0's preflight has already proven no\n307\t--    unknown kinds exist past the assertion. We use 'article'\n308\t--    rather than 'unreachable' so that the SQL is still a valid\n309\t--    total mapping in isolation — defence in depth without a\n310\t--    second contract surface to keep in lockstep with D3.\n311\tINSERT INTO vector_default(\n312\t  rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n313\t)\n314\tSELECT\n315\t  s.rowid,\n316\t  s.embedding,\n317\t  vec_quantize_binary(s.embedding),\n318\t  CASE s.kind\n319\t    WHEN 'email'   THEN 'email'\n320\t    WHEN 'article' THEN 'article'\n321\t    WHEN 'paper'   THEN 'paper'\n322\t    WHEN 'meeting' THEN 'meeting'\n323\t    WHEN 'note'    THEN 'note'\n324\t    WHEN 'todo'    THEN 'todo'\n325\t    WHEN 'doc'     THEN 'article'  -- AC-013 fixture coercion; see D3.\n326\t    ELSE 'article'                 -- unreachable past sub-step 0; see note above.\n327\t  END AS source_type,\n328\t  s.kind,\n329\t  strftime('%s', 'now')\n330\tFROM _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 s;\n331\t\n332\t-- 4. Drop the staging + assertion tables.\n333\tDROP TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0;\n334\tDROP TABLE _vec0_migration_assertion;\n335\t```\n336\t\n337\tWhy the D3 mapping is inlined in SQL (and not a Rust loop): the\n338\t`Migration` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54` is\n339\t`{ step_id, sql: &'static str }` — pure SQL, no Rust callback\n340\textension point. The CASE WHEN above is the literal byte-for-byte\n341\ttranscription of the D3 mapping table; a Rust-side loop would\n342\trequire extending the schema crate's migration trait (a\n343\tlarger-blast-radius change that this slice does not authorize).\n344\tThe CASE shape also avoids registering an ad-hoc Rust scalar\n345\tfunction on the migration connection. The D3 helper\n346\t`resolve_source_type` (defined in this memo for the writer\n347\tsites D5/D7) is the canonical lookup at write time; the CASE\n348\tabove is the migration-time mirror of that table and must be\n349\tkept in lockstep with it — P1-IMPL adds a co-located assertion\n350\tin tests/migration coverage to catch drift.\n351\t\n352\tProperties of this migration step:\n353\t\n354\t- **Synchronous.** All four sub-steps run inside the same\n355\t  `apply_one` transaction (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`),\n356\t  on the migration thread, before `migrate_with_event_sink`\n357\t  returns. There is no async hand-off.\n358\t- **No embedder rerun.** The f32 blobs are copied verbatim from\n359\t  `vector_default.embedding` into the staging table and back\n360\t  out. The embedder is never invoked.\n361\t- **`vec_quantize_binary` call site.** SQL-side at the\n362\t  repopulation `INSERT`'s SELECT projection, once per row,\n363\t  evaluated against the f32 blob already materialised in the\n364\t  staging row. No Rust-side bit math; no double scan of the\n365\t  source blob.\n366\t- **Atomicity.** `apply_one` wraps the whole SQL blob in\n367\t  `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT` and `ROLLBACK`s on any error\n368\t  (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`). If any sub-step\n369\t  fails, the migration is rolled back, `PRAGMA user_version`\n370\t  stays at the previous value, and the next open re-attempts\n371\t  the migration cleanly. The staging + sentinel tables are part\n372\t  of the same transaction and are dropped on rollback alongside\n373\t  the would-be new `vector_default`.\n374\t- **Fail-fast on unknown kinds.** Sub-step 0 above creates a\n375\t  `_vec0_migration_assertion(check_passes INTEGER NOT NULL\n376\t  CHECK(check_passes = 1))` sentinel table and INSERTs the\n377\t  result of an `EXISTS` probe against the locked vocabulary\n378\t  (incl. `doc`). If any row in `_fathomdb_vector_rows` has a\n379\t  `kind` outside `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo,\n380\t  doc}`, the probe evaluates to 0, the CHECK constraint fires\n381\t  `SQLITE_CONSTRAINT` at INSERT time, and `apply_one` rolls\n382\t  back the whole step. CHECK constraints on regular SQL tables\n383\t  are a built-in SQLite primitive\n384\t  (https://www.sqlite.org/lang_createtable.html#check_constraints);\n385\t  no extension and no trigger required. (Alternative shapes\n386\t  considered: a single-statement CTE with a forced UNIQUE\n387\t  violation, or a Rust-side preflight in `open_with_migrations`\n388\t  before `migrate_with_event_sink`. Neither is necessary here\n389\t  because `apply_one` calls `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)`\n390\t  — multi-statement semantics, re-verified at\n391\t  `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:276` — so the preflight can be a\n392\t  prefix statement in the same SQL string.) This is what\n393\t  encodes the D3 \"writer error on unknown kind\" rule at\n394\t  migration time; the writer enforces it independently at\n395\t  steady-state write time via `resolve_source_type` in D3 / D5.\n396\t- **NOT NULL enforcement at write time.** vec0 metadata columns\n397\t  do not have a declarative `NOT NULL` constraint in the\n398\t  sqlite-vec DDL surface\n399\t  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);\n400\t  non-nullability is contract-enforced by the migration and by\n401\t  the D5/D7 writers. Pack 1 writers always supply all five\n402\t  metadata columns; the migration always supplies them (the\n403\t  CASE's ELSE branch is `'article'`, not NULL, and the\n404\t  sub-step 0 preflight has already proven the ELSE branch is\n405\t  unreachable for in-tree corpora). No row can land with a NULL.\n406\t\n407\tMigration cost: dominated by two sequential scans of the\n408\texisting 3 GB f32 corpus on the 1 M-row fixture — one for the\n409\tstaging `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 1) and one for the\n410\trepopulation `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 3). The\n411\t`vec_quantize_binary` work is a sign-bit fold per coordinate,\n412\tnegligible relative to the I/O. The working budget remains the\n413\t60-90 s estimate from ADR § 4. The migration **does not** re-run\n414\tthe embedder, so the AC-013 562 s seed time\n415\t(`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`)\n416\tis **not** a comparable baseline — that figure includes embedder\n417\twork this migration avoids by construction. A concrete\n418\tmeasurement lands in P1-IMPL's GREEN gate.\n419\t\n420\tIdempotence: `PRAGMA user_version` already guards re-entry\n421\t(`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:234`, `:277`). On the second open\n422\tthe migration step is skipped because `migration.step_id <=\n423\tbefore`, and `vector_default` keeps the rows from the first\n424\tpass.\n425\t\n426\t### Rejected alternative — repopulate via `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n427\t\n428\tThe fix-1 draft of D4 proposed driving repopulation through\n429\t`Engine::rebuild_vec0` (`lib.rs:1947`), which calls\n430\t`run_rebuild` -> `rebuild_shadow_state` with `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n431\t(`lib.rs:2234-2289`). Codex fix-1 review (finding 1,\n432\t`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`)\n433\tcorrectly flagged that this path:\n434\t\n435\t- Is asynchronous. `rebuild_shadow_state` only truncates vec0\n436\t  state and resets the projection cursor; the actual\n437\t  re-derivation runs on the projection scheduler. The test at\n438\t  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`\n439\t  observes `rebuild_vec0` returns immediately and polls\n440\t  `projection_status_for_test` to wait for the async drain.\n441\t- Re-runs the embedder. The projection scheduler's\n442\t  `run_projection_job` calls `embedder.embed(&job.body)` at\n443\t  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2528-2557` for\n444\t  every row it re-derives.\n445\t- Is therefore not equivalent to copying the existing f32\n446\t  blobs: it would multiply the migration cost by the embedder\n447\t  work the migration is specifically designed to avoid, and it\n448\t  would leak a window in which `vector_default` is empty before\n449\t  the async drain catches up.\n450\t\n451\tThe staged-copy migration above replaces this path entirely.\n452\t`rebuild_vec0` remains as it is in tree for the operator-driven\n453\t\"rebuild from canonical\" tool; Pack 1's migration does not call\n454\tit.\n455\t\n456\t## D5 — Writer transaction shape\n457\t\n458\tThe writer site is `commit_projection_outcomes` at\n459\t`lib.rs:2845-2853`. The double-write lands in the **same**\n460\t`tx.execute` sequence between the existing\n461\t`_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert and the existing\n462\t`record_projection_terminal` call. No extra commit; no extra\n463\tlock; no extra connection.\n464\t\n465\t**Decision: compute `vec_quantize_binary` inside the SQL\n466\tstatement (single `INSERT` per row), not in Rust ahead of bind.**\n467\t\n468\tThe rewritten statement:\n469\t\n470\t```rust\n471\ttx.execute(\n472\t    \"INSERT OR IGNORE INTO vector_default(\n473\t        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n474\t     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n475\t    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n476\t)?;\n477\t```\n478\t\n479\tJustification (one paragraph):\n480\t\n481\tThe SQL-side shape keeps the f32 blob single-bound (one rusqlite\n482\t`Vec<u8>` allocation, one bind), lets sqlite-vec compute the\n483\tbit-vector against its own internal blob layout (which is what\n484\tthe Pack 2 reader will also see), and avoids pulling a Rust-side\n485\t`vec_quantize_binary` dependency or re-implementing the sign-bit\n486\tfold in the engine crate. The \"double-evaluation\" concern (vec0\n487\tmaterialising `?2` twice) is a non-issue because the binary\n488\tquantization is a single sequential sign-bit pass over the same\n489\tin-memory blob — both passes operate on the same bound parameter\n490\tand the SQLite parameter store does not copy. The Rust-side\n491\talternative would (a) require either linking against sqlite-vec's\n492\tC symbols from Rust or shipping a hand-rolled sign-fold, (b)\n493\tdouble the f32 footprint at bind time, and (c) couple the engine\n494\tcrate to the on-the-wire bit format which is sqlite-vec's\n495\tinternal concern. SQL-side is the cleaner contract surface.\n496\t\n497\t## D6 — `vec_quantize_binary()` contract validation plan\n498\t\n499\tThe Pack 1 RED test is a round-trip:\n500\t\n501\t1. Build a known f32 vector `v` of length `<dim>` whose sign\n502\t   pattern is hand-checkable.\n503\t2. Insert via the writer path.\n504\t3. Assert `vec_distance_hamming(embedding_bin, vec_quantize_binary(vec_f32(v))) = 0`.\n505\t\n506\tSpecified fixture (deterministic, no normalisation involved):\n507\t\n508\t```\n509\tdim = 768.\n510\tv[i] = +1.0 for i in 0..384, -1.0 for i in 384..768.\n511\t```\n512\t\n513\tExpected `embedding_bin`: 384 set bits in the leading half, 384\n514\tclear bits in the trailing half. Popcount = 384. The exact bit\n515\tordering (LSB-first within each byte vs MSB-first) is an\n516\tsqlite-vec internal contract; the round-trip via\n517\t`vec_quantize_binary` guarantees both writer and reader see the\n518\tsame packing, which is the only invariant the engine relies on.\n519\t`vec_distance_hamming` against the same vector binarised the same\n520\tway must be 0.\n521\t\n522\tOne fixture is sufficient. The previously-drafted secondary\n523\t\"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed (its claim that\n524\t`normalise([1,-1,1,-1,...])` and the half/half vector share\n525\t\"identical sign patterns at every coordinate\" is wrong — one is\n526\thalf-positive/half-negative, the other alternates — see codex\n527\tverdict finding 3). If P1-IMPL wants a second fixture for\n528\tdefence-in-depth, the recommended shape is a vector that is +1\n529\ton every fourth coordinate and -1 elsewhere\n530\t(`v3[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0` for dim=768): popcount\n531\tof the quantization is exactly 192 set bits, trivially\n532\thand-checked, and clearly distinct from the half/half fixture's\n533\tpopcount of 384.\n534\t\n535\tValidation status: **empirical validation deferred to P1-IMPL's\n536\tRED test.** A one-shot `sqlite3` confirmation against a temp DB\n537\twith `sqlite-vec` loaded was considered for this memo but\n538\trejected because (a) the Rust crate is the binding the writer\n539\tactually uses and the sqlite3 CLI binding is a separate code\n540\tpath, (b) P1-IMPL's RED test exercises the engine writer\n541\tend-to-end which is the only contract that matters, and (c) the\n542\tbinary-quant guide\n543\t(https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)\n544\talready documents the round-trip shape and `vec_distance_hamming`\n545\tbehaviour. If the RED test surfaces a contract surprise (signed\n546\tzero, NaN, byte-order), that is HITL escalation territory per\n547\tthe ADR § 6 / \"vec_quantize_binary() input expectations\" — not\n548\tsomething this design memo can resolve in advance.\n549\t\n550\tOpen-item linkage: the ADR § 6 third bullet calls out the\n551\tfixture's \"atypically friendly\" sign-pattern concentration (mass\n552\ton 6 of 768 coordinates per `tests/perf_gates.rs:317`). That is a\n553\trecall-headroom concern for Pack 2, not a contract concern for\n554\tPack 1. Pack 1's RED test is correctness, not recall.\n555\t\n556\t## D7 — Second writer site (test-only)\n557\t\n558\tConfirmed. The test-only helper at\n559\t`Engine::write_vector_for_test` (`lib.rs:1806-1845`) is a second\n560\tingest path that inserts into `vector_default` (line 1838). Pack 1\n561\tmust update this site in lockstep with `commit_projection_outcomes`\n562\tor it will violate the NOT NULL contract on `embedding_bin` /\n563\t`source_type` / `kind` / `created_at` and break every test that\n564\tgoes through `write_vector_for_test`.\n565\t\n566\tThe rewritten test helper insert is structurally identical to D5:\n567\t\n568\t```rust\n569\ttx.execute(\n570\t    \"INSERT INTO vector_default(\n571\t        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n572\t     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n573\t    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n574\t)?;\n575\t```\n576\t\n577\tPack 1 implementation MUST touch both:\n578\t\n579\t- `lib.rs:1832-1841` (test helper writer; the\n580\t  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert at :1832-1836 also needs the\n581\t  same `kind` value flow as `commit_projection_outcomes`).\n582\t- `lib.rs:2845-2852` (production writer; D5 site).\n583\t\n584\tNo other writer site touches `vector_default`. The delete sites\n585\t(`lib.rs:2177`, `:2265`) are unaffected — they target the row by\n586\trowid and the column changes are append-only at the schema level.\n587\tThe writer-loop pins at `:2174`, `:2181`, `:2242` are not touched\n588\t(they DELETE-by-rowid or operate on the shadow `_fathomdb_vector_rows`\n589\ttable, not on the metadata columns being added).\n590\t\n591\t## D8 — Reader-path NO-OP guarantee\n592\t\n593\tThe Pack 2 reader rewrite is out of scope. The Pack 1 question is:\n594\tdoes the **existing** reader at `read_search_in_tx`\n595\t(`lib.rs:2317-2323`) keep working over the migrated schema?\n596\t\n597\tThe existing query is:\n598\t\n599\t```sql\n600\tSELECT rowid FROM vector_default\n601\tWHERE embedding MATCH vec_f32(?1)\n602\tORDER BY distance\n603\tLIMIT 10\n604\t```\n605\t\n606\t**Decision: confirmed no-op. The existing reader continues to\n607\treturn identical results post-migration.**\n608\t\n609\tReasoning:\n610\t\n611\t- The `embedding` column is **retained** (ADR § 2.1 \"the f32\n612\t  `embedding` column is retained\"). Its declared type\n613\t  `float[<dim>]` is unchanged.\n614\t- vec0's MATCH semantics dispatch on the column referenced in the\n615\t  predicate; adding sibling vector columns\n616\t  (`embedding_bin bit[<dim>]`) and metadata columns\n617\t  (`source_type`, `kind`, `created_at`) does not alter the\n618\t  semantics of `embedding MATCH vec_f32(?)`.\n619\t- The metadata + partition-key release blog\n620\t  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html)\n621\t  demonstrates a vec0 declaration with `partition key` + plain\n622\t  metadata columns + the vector column, queried by the vector\n623\t  predicate alone; the additional columns are filterable via\n624\t  `WHERE` but do not become mandatory in the query shape.\n625\t- The Pack 1 migration preserves the `rowid <-> write_cursor`\n626\t  identity by JOIN-ing `vector_default.rowid` into the staging\n627\t  table (D4 sub-step 1: `SELECT v.rowid, v.embedding, r.kind\n628\t  FROM vector_default v JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid\n629\t  = v.rowid`) and then repopulating the recreated\n630\t  `vector_default` with the same staged rowids (D4 sub-step 3:\n631\t  `INSERT INTO vector_default(rowid, ...) SELECT s.rowid, ...\n632\t  FROM _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 s`); the writer-loop\n633\t  pins at `lib.rs:2174-2175`, `:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265` continue\n634\t  to hold.\n635\t\n636\tAC-013 latency therefore stays at 2048 / 2327 ms post-Pack 1\n637\t(matches the ADR § 4 / handoff § 1 stated contract). AC-019\n638\tstays at its existing bound. AC-012 / AC-017 / AC-018 / AC-020\n639\tare untouched because they do not query `vector_default`.\n640\t\n641\t## Open escalations\n642\t\n643\tNone. All eight decisions resolved against repo + cited external\n644\tdocs. The pre-existing open items in the ADR § 6 (\"final numeric\n645\tbudgets\", \"K-value selection\", \"fixture-friendliness for recall\")\n646\tare Pack 2 concerns and are not affected by Pack 1.\n647\t\n648\t## Fix-1 changelog\n649\t\n650\tAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n651\t`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`.\n652\t\n653\t- **Fix 1.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D3 no longer extends\n654\t  the HITL-locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary. The\n655\t  synthetic AC-013 fixture kind `\"doc\"` is now coerced at the\n656\t  writer to `source_type = \"article\"`. The locked vocabulary\n657\t  `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo}` holds exactly;\n658\t  no HITL re-open required. Mapping table + rationale + reject\n659\t  list updated in D3.\n660\t- **Fix 1.2 (verdict finding 2, high).** D4 migration rewritten\n661\t  to use the engine's real migration framework:\n662\t  `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at `lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n663\t  `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +\n664\t  `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7\n665\t  has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in\n666\t  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`). (Repopulation shape later replaced by\n667\t  the fix-2 staged copy; see Fix-2 changelog below.)\n668\t- **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary\n669\t  \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The\n670\t  half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test\n671\t  fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture\n672\t  (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is\n673\t  recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.\n674\t\n675\t## Fix-2 changelog\n676\t\n677\tAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n678\t`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`\n679\t(one new high finding on D4's repopulation semantics).\n680\t\n681\t- **Fix 2.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D4 repopulation no\n682\t  longer routes through `Engine::rebuild_vec0` /\n683\t  `rebuild_shadow_state` (`RebuildKind::Vec0`). Verified against\n684\t  the actual code: `run_projection_job` at\n685\t  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2523-2557` calls\n686\t  `embedder.embed(&job.body)` per row, and the rebuild test at\n687\t  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`\n688\t  locks in async drain semantics — both contradict the fix-1\n689\t  claim that repopulation is synchronous and avoids the\n690\t  embedder. D4 is replaced with a single SQL migration step\n691\t  executed under `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`,\n692\t  re-verified): (1) stage existing `vector_default` rows\n693\t  JOIN-ed with `_fathomdb_vector_rows.kind` into a regular\n694\t  staging table, (2) `DROP TABLE vector_default` + recreate\n695\t  with the Pack 1 schema, (3) `INSERT ... SELECT` from staging\n696\t  with `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side and a CASE expression\n697\t  rendering the D3 `kind -> source_type` map, (4) drop the\n698\t  staging table. Properties recorded explicitly: synchronous,\n699\t  no embedder rerun, atomic under `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`/`COMMIT`,\n700\t  `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side once per row. Cost citation\n701\t  updated: the AC-013 562 s seed figure is no longer cited as\n702\t  a baseline because it includes embedder work this migration\n703\t  avoids; budget remains the 60-90 s ADR § 4 estimate. A\n704\t  \"Rejected alternative\" subsection added under D4 explaining\n705\t  why `rebuild_vec0` is not used.\n706\t- **Fix 2.2 (consequence).** D4 SQL-only migration shape is\n707\t  justified against the actual `Migration { step_id: u32, sql:\n708\t  &'static str }` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`\n709\t  (re-verified) — pure SQL, no Rust callback extension point.\n710\t  CASE WHEN is the migration-time mirror of the D3 helper\n711\t  `resolve_source_type`; P1-IMPL is directed to add a\n712\t  co-located drift-detection assertion.\n713\t\n714\t## Fix-3 changelog\n715\t\n716\tAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n717\t`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-2-review-20260527T135041Z.md`\n718\t(one high, one medium, one low — all localized to D4 internal\n719\tconsistency and one stale D8 citation).\n720\t\n721\t- **Fix 3.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D4's \"unknown kind =\n722\t  error\" rule no longer relies on the unsupported `ELSE NULL` +\n723\t  vec0 NOT NULL combination. The migration SQL now prefixes the\n724\t  staged-copy with a real fail-fast preflight: a\n725\t  `_vec0_migration_assertion(check_passes INTEGER NOT NULL\n726\t  CHECK(check_passes = 1))` sentinel table whose INSERT computes\n727\t  `CASE WHEN EXISTS(... kind NOT IN locked-vocab ...) THEN 0\n728\t  ELSE 1 END`. An unknown kind drives `check_passes = 0`, the\n729\t  CHECK constraint fires `SQLITE_CONSTRAINT` at INSERT time, and\n730\t  `apply_one`'s ROLLBACK undoes the whole step (sentinel table\n731\t  included). The CHECK primitive is vanilla SQLite (cited:\n732\t  https://www.sqlite.org/lang_createtable.html#check_constraints);\n733\t  no extension, no trigger required. Multi-statement viability\n734\t  re-verified empirically against `apply_one` at\n735\t  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`, which\n736\t  calls `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)` (line 276) — batch\n737\t  semantics, so the preflight can be a prefix statement in the\n738\t  same SQL string. The repopulating CASE keeps `ELSE 'article'`\n739\t  (defence-in-depth past the assertion; justified inline in D4).\n740\t- **Fix 3.2 (verdict finding 2, medium).** D4 no longer claims\n741\t  a Rust-rendered `<now>` literal or any migration-build-time\n742\t  timestamp construction. The `created_at` column is filled by\n743\t  `strftime('%s','now')` evaluated at INSERT time inside the\n744\t  migration SQL. The uniform-timestamp guarantee is per INSERT\n745\t  statement: SQLite's date/time functions return the same value\n746\t  across all rows in a single statement when no varying\n747\t  arguments are passed (cited:\n748\t  https://www.sqlite.org/lang_datefunc.html). The stale\n749\t  `open_with_migrations` (`lib.rs:1119`) anchor is removed from\n750\t  D4 — no Rust path is involved in the timestamp.\n751\t- **Fix 3.3 (verdict finding 3, low).** D8's stale `INSERT INTO\n752\t  vector_default_v2 ... SELECT v.rowid` proof point (left over\n753\t  from the pre-fix-2 sibling-table draft) is replaced with the\n754\t  staged-copy proof: rowid is the explicit JOIN key in the\n755\t  staging INSERT (`SELECT v.rowid, ... FROM vector_default v\n756\t  JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid = v.rowid`), and the\n757\t  recreated `vector_default` receives the same staged rowid in\n758\t  the repopulation INSERT. Conclusion (rowid <-> write_cursor\n759\t  identity preserved; writer-loop pins at `lib.rs:2174-2175`,\n760\t  `:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265` continue to hold) is unchanged.\n761\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e9a78e19-c91a-49c2-b696-e44747a28d5b","uuid":"1a32c3b7-5016-417e-b878-e6b9e0906859","timestamp":"2026-05-27T14:04:06.486Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-P1-IMPL-20260527T140358Z/dev/design/0.7.0-vector-quant-pack1.md","content":"---\ntitle: 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\ndate: 2026-05-27\ntarget_release: 0.7.0\ndesc: Pack 1 schema-migration + ingest double-write decisions for\n  the binary-quantization data-encoding change locked by\n  ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md.\nblast_radius: src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs (schema +\n  writer); src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/perf_gates.rs\n  (existing fixture continuity); dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md\n  (implements its Pack 1 section).\nstatus: draft fix-3 (consumed by Pack 1 implementation)\n---\n\n# 0.7.0 Vector binary-quant — Pack 1 design\n\nThis memo resolves the open design questions called out in\n`dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-PERF-VECTOR-QUANT-HANDOFF.md` § \"Pack 1\"\nand § \"Open items the implementing agent should escalate to HITL\"\nso that Pack 1 implementation can land mechanically. Pairs with\nADR-0.7.0-vector-binary-quant.md (which records the *what*); this\nmemo records the *exact shape*.\n\nScope: Pack 1 only — schema migration + writer double-write. No\nreader changes. The Pack 2 query rewrite is out of scope for this\nmemo and is owned by a separate design pass when Pack 2 starts.\n\n## D1 — Sibling column vs. sibling table\n\n**Decision: sibling column on `vector_default`.**\n\nThe migrated declaration is:\n\n```\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n  embedding float[<dim>],\n  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n  source_type TEXT partition key,\n  kind TEXT,\n  created_at INTEGER\n);\n```\n\n(`<dim>` = 768 for the current default profile; the existing\n`ensure_vector_partition` builds the dimension from\n`load_default_profile` at `lib.rs:3278-3283`.)\n\n- Alternatives weighed: sibling table `vector_default_bin` (one\n  extra join on every read; fan-out cost on the Pack 2 reader; two\n  inserts per row instead of one; two DELETE sites in every\n  excise / rebuild path — `lib.rs:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265`).\n- Citation: the sqlite-vec binary-quant guide demonstrates the\n  exact mixed-flavour declaration\n  `create virtual table vec_movies using vec0(synopsis_embedding\n  float[768], synopsis_embedding_coarse bit[768])`\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html);\n  confirmed empirically by WebFetch on 2026-05-27 against the\n  same page.\n\nThe sibling-column shape is the default in the handoff\n(§ 1.1) and in the ADR (§ 2 / Pack 1.1). The sibling-table\nfallback remains documented in both as a recovery path **only if**\nthe 16-metadata-column cap is exceeded (see D2) — that is not the\ncase for Pack 1.\n\n## D2 — Metadata column inventory (vec0 16-col cap)\n\nvec0 caps metadata columns at 16 and partition keys at 4\n(`dev/notes/0.7.0-vector-cost-research.md:70-71`). The Pack 1\nschema lands the minimum-viable set with headroom for the\nreal-workload extension already foreseen by the ADR and the\nHITL doc.\n\nPack 1 column inventory on `vector_default`:\n\n| # | Column            | Type           | Role                  | Source                                                         |\n|---|-------------------|----------------|-----------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------|\n| 0 | `rowid`           | INTEGER        | (implicit pk)         | `cursor` (existing — `lib.rs:2845-2851`).                      |\n| 1 | `embedding`       | `float[<dim>]` | vector                | existing — `vec_quantize_binary` input + Pack 2 rerank.        |\n| 2 | `embedding_bin`   | `bit[<dim>]`   | quantized vector      | `vec_quantize_binary(embedding)` at write time.                |\n| 3 | `source_type`     | `TEXT`         | **partition key**     | derived from `kind` per D3.                                    |\n| 4 | `kind`            | `TEXT`         | metadata col          | existing `ProjectionOutcome::Success.kind` (`lib.rs:2841`).    |\n| 5 | `created_at`      | `INTEGER`     | metadata col          | UNIX seconds at write time (mirrors `excised_at` pattern at `lib.rs:2206`). |\n\nHeadroom: **11 free metadata column slots + 3 free partition-key\nslots** after Pack 1.\n\nDeferred to Pack 2 / 0.7.1 (NOT landed in Pack 1):\n\n- `tags`, `project_mentions` — named in the handoff § 1.1 but not\n  populated by today's writer; the chunk record carries no such\n  field. Wiring requires upstream code changes that are out of\n  scope for the Pack 1 schema-only slice. Headroom preserved.\n- Any per-source metadata (sender, doc URL, etc.) — corpus-card\n  work; lives outside Pack 1.\n\nRationale for landing `created_at` now: it is the one non-\ncontroversial metadata field with a deterministic write-time\nsource (clock at insert), it is cheap to add to the migration,\nand the alternative (a second migration in 0.7.1 to add it) costs\nanother ~64 s rebuild of the 1 M-row corpus. Adds zero\nimplementation risk because the writer site already calls\n`SystemTime::now()` for the excise-audit path (`lib.rs:2206`).\n\n## D3 — `kind` -> `source_type` mapping\n\nThe locked `source_type` vocabulary is\n{`email`, `article`, `paper`, `meeting`, `note`, `todo`}\n(`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137`; cardinality\n\"~6\" in the ADR § 2).\n\nThe current writer at `commit_projection_outcomes`\n(`lib.rs:2841`) receives `kind: String` from\n`ProjectionOutcome::Success`. The only kind exercised by tests\ntoday is `\"doc\"` (AC-013 fixture seed at\n`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), a synthetic name introduced for the\nperformance fixture and **not** in the locked source_type\nvocabulary.\n\n**Decision: the locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary holds\nunchanged. The synthetic test fixture kind `\"doc\"` is coerced\nat the writer to `source_type = \"article\"`; the vocabulary is\nnot extended.** No HITL re-open required — the lock at\n`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` is honored\nexactly.\n\nMapping table (Pack 1, deterministic, total):\n\n| Incoming `kind` value | Resolved `source_type` |\n|-----------------------|------------------------|\n| `\"email\"`             | `email`                |\n| `\"article\"`           | `article`              |\n| `\"paper\"`             | `paper`                |\n| `\"meeting\"`           | `meeting`              |\n| `\"note\"`              | `note`                 |\n| `\"todo\"`              | `todo`                 |\n| `\"doc\"` (synthetic test fixture from `tests/perf_gates.rs:350`) | `article` (coerced) |\n| anything else         | **writer error** — fail the projection outcome (`EngineError::Storage`); do not silently default. |\n\nRationale for the `doc` -> `article` coercion: AC-013 seeds\nsynthetic doc-shaped bodies (long-form text) that are the most\nsemantically aligned with the `article` source within the locked\n6-value set. The coercion (a) preserves the partition_key\nutility for the AC-013 fixture rows (they aggregate under a real\nsource_type bucket the corpus-build work will also populate),\n(b) avoids any test churn — the fixture continues to write\n`kind=\"doc\"`; only the resolved `source_type` differs, (c)\nmatches what `CORPUS-1` (CNN/DailyMail acquisition, commit\n`27ab8df`) will land as the production article source. The\ncoercion is writer-internal; the canonical `kind` value is\npreserved verbatim in the `kind` metadata column (and in\n`_fathomdb_vector_rows`), so any consumer needing to distinguish\nfixture rows from corpus rows can still do so by reading `kind`.\n\nRejected alternatives:\n\n- \"Add `doc` as a 7th `source_type` value\" — extends the\n  HITL-locked vocabulary without authorization. This was the\n  original draft and is the blocking finding in the codex\n  verdict (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`\n  finding 1).\n- \"Rename the fixture kind from `doc` to one of the 6 locked\n  values\" — touches every test that reads the AC-013 fixture\n  (larger blast radius than a writer-side coercion).\n- \"Leave `source_type` nullable for unmapped kinds\" — loses the\n  partition_key benefit for the AC-013 fixture and breaks the\n  \"partition_key is locked\" guarantee in HITL Q5.\n\nCitation: HITL lock at\n`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` (vocabulary +\n\"supersedes the `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff\").\n\nThe mapping is implemented in a single Rust helper:\n\n```rust\nfn resolve_source_type(kind: &str) -> Result<&'static str, EngineError> {\n    Ok(match kind {\n        \"email\" => \"email\",\n        \"article\" => \"article\",\n        \"paper\" => \"paper\",\n        \"meeting\" => \"meeting\",\n        \"note\" => \"note\",\n        \"todo\" => \"todo\",\n        // Synthetic AC-013 test fixture; coerced to \"article\" so\n        // the 6-value HITL lock holds. See D3 rationale above.\n        \"doc\" => \"article\",\n        _ => return Err(EngineError::Storage),\n    })\n}\n```\n\n(no allocator pressure; returns `&'static str`; used at both\nwriter sites in D7.)\n\n## D4 — NOT NULL + migration strategy\n\nvec0 virtual tables in sqlite-vec `=0.1.7` (this repo's pin)\nsupport neither `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (a SQLite-level\nrule for virtual tables — https://www.sqlite.org/vtab.html) nor\n`ALTER TABLE ... RENAME` (rename support landed in sqlite-vec\n`v0.1.10-alpha.2`, April 2026, per the sqlite-vec release\nhistory). The migration is therefore a `DROP TABLE` + recreate\nunder the same name. Repopulation must be **synchronous and\nin-transaction**, copying the existing f32 blobs verbatim — it\nmust NOT go through the engine's async rebuild driver.\n\n**Decision: land NOT NULL constraints from the start. The\nmigration is a single SQL migration step that (a) stages the\nexisting f32 rows + kind into a regular SQL table, (b) drops\nand recreates `vector_default` with the new schema under the\nsame name, (c) repopulates `vector_default` from the staging\ntable with `vec_quantize_binary` evaluated SQL-side at INSERT\nbind, and (d) drops the staging table — all inside the migration\nframework's `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` / `COMMIT` envelope. The writer\nenforces non-nullability from commit zero.**\n\nSchema versioning is owned by the engine's real migration\nframework: `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at\n`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1238`, which is a\nthin re-export of `fathomdb_schema::migrate_with_event_sink`\nimplemented at `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:218-271`.\n`apply_one` (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`)\nwraps each migration step in `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT`,\ncalling `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)` followed by\n`pragma_update(PRAGMA_USER_VERSION, step_id)`, and rolling back\non any error. `Migration` itself is `{ step_id: u32, sql:\n&'static str }` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`) — pure SQL,\nno Rust callback hook. The new vec0 schema lands as a new\n`fathomdb_schema::Migration` step appended to the existing\nmigration array passed into `open_with_migrations`\n(`lib.rs:1119-1131`); `migrate_with_event_sink` bumps\n`PRAGMA user_version` on commit and gates re-entry on the same\nsentinel, so re-opens are naturally idempotent. The previously\nproposed `operational_mutations` schema stamp is **not** the\nschema-version owner — that collection is excise audit rows\n(`lib.rs:2217-2221`) — and is dropped from the design.\n\nMigration step (Pack 1) — single SQL blob, executed atomically\nby `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`):\n\n```sql\n-- Step body. Runs inside BEGIN IMMEDIATE ... COMMIT supplied\n-- by apply_one (fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288), which\n-- invokes conn.execute_batch(migration.sql) — i.e. the migration\n-- string is treated as a multi-statement batch (re-verified\n-- against fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:276). Sub-steps below may\n-- therefore be separate SQL statements in the same string.\n--\n-- <dim> is rendered at migration-build time (768 for the default\n-- profile, see ensure_vector_partition at lib.rs:3278-3283).\n-- created_at is filled by strftime('%s','now') evaluated at\n-- INSERT time. Per SQLite's date/time function contract\n-- (https://www.sqlite.org/lang_datefunc.html), built-in date/time\n-- functions return the same value for every row within a single\n-- SQL statement when no varying arguments are passed; the whole\n-- corpus is therefore backfilled with one uniform created_at\n-- value — no Rust-side timestamp rendering, no migration-build-\n-- time substitution.\n\n-- 0. Preflight assertion: abort the migration if any existing\n--    kind is not in the locked source_type vocabulary (incl. the\n--    doc->article coercion in D3). The CHECK constraint on\n--    _vec0_migration_assertion.check_passes fires SQLITE_CONSTRAINT\n--    at INSERT time when check_passes evaluates to 0, which\n--    aborts the migration; apply_one's ROLLBACK undoes the\n--    sentinel-table CREATE alongside it. CHECK constraints on\n--    regular tables are vanilla SQLite (no extension needed):\n--    https://www.sqlite.org/lang_createtable.html#check_constraints\nCREATE TEMP TABLE _vec0_migration_assertion(\n  check_passes INTEGER NOT NULL CHECK(check_passes = 1)\n);\nINSERT INTO _vec0_migration_assertion(check_passes)\nSELECT CASE WHEN EXISTS (\n  SELECT 1 FROM _fathomdb_vector_rows\n  WHERE kind NOT IN ('email','article','paper','meeting','note','todo','doc')\n) THEN 0 ELSE 1 END;\n\n-- 1. Stage existing f32 blobs + kind into a regular SQL table.\n--    _fathomdb_vector_rows.kind is the source of truth for the\n--    existing rows' kind (writer site at lib.rs:2845-2853).\nCREATE TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 (\n  rowid     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,\n  embedding BLOB NOT NULL,\n  kind      TEXT NOT NULL\n);\nINSERT INTO _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0(rowid, embedding, kind)\nSELECT v.rowid, v.embedding, r.kind\n  FROM vector_default v\n  JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid = v.rowid;\n\n-- 2. Drop the old vec0 table and recreate under the same name.\nDROP TABLE vector_default;\nCREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(\n  embedding float[<dim>],\n  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],\n  source_type TEXT partition key,\n  kind TEXT,\n  created_at INTEGER\n);\n\n-- 3. Repopulate from staging. vec_quantize_binary runs SQL-side\n--    once per row against the existing f32 blob; source_type is\n--    coerced from kind via the D3 mapping using a CASE\n--    expression. The ELSE branch is 'article' (matching the\n--    D3 doc->article coercion); it is in principle unreachable\n--    because sub-step 0's preflight has already proven no\n--    unknown kinds exist past the assertion. We use 'article'\n--    rather than 'unreachable' so that the SQL is still a valid\n--    total mapping in isolation — defence in depth without a\n--    second contract surface to keep in lockstep with D3.\nINSERT INTO vector_default(\n  rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n)\nSELECT\n  s.rowid,\n  s.embedding,\n  vec_quantize_binary(s.embedding),\n  CASE s.kind\n    WHEN 'email'   THEN 'email'\n    WHEN 'article' THEN 'article'\n    WHEN 'paper'   THEN 'paper'\n    WHEN 'meeting' THEN 'meeting'\n    WHEN 'note'    THEN 'note'\n    WHEN 'todo'    THEN 'todo'\n    WHEN 'doc'     THEN 'article'  -- AC-013 fixture coercion; see D3.\n    ELSE 'article'                 -- unreachable past sub-step 0; see note above.\n  END AS source_type,\n  s.kind,\n  strftime('%s', 'now')\nFROM _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 s;\n\n-- 4. Drop the staging + assertion tables.\nDROP TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0;\nDROP TABLE _vec0_migration_assertion;\n```\n\nWhy the D3 mapping is inlined in SQL (and not a Rust loop): the\n`Migration` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54` is\n`{ step_id, sql: &'static str }` — pure SQL, no Rust callback\nextension point. The CASE WHEN above is the literal byte-for-byte\ntranscription of the D3 mapping table; a Rust-side loop would\nrequire extending the schema crate's migration trait (a\nlarger-blast-radius change that this slice does not authorize).\nThe CASE shape also avoids registering an ad-hoc Rust scalar\nfunction on the migration connection. The D3 helper\n`resolve_source_type` (defined in this memo for the writer\nsites D5/D7) is the canonical lookup at write time; the CASE\nabove is the migration-time mirror of that table and must be\nkept in lockstep with it — P1-IMPL adds a co-located assertion\nin tests/migration coverage to catch drift.\n\nProperties of this migration step:\n\n- **Synchronous.** All four sub-steps run inside the same\n  `apply_one` transaction (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`),\n  on the migration thread, before `migrate_with_event_sink`\n  returns. There is no async hand-off.\n- **No embedder rerun.** The f32 blobs are copied verbatim from\n  `vector_default.embedding` into the staging table and back\n  out. The embedder is never invoked.\n- **`vec_quantize_binary` call site.** SQL-side at the\n  repopulation `INSERT`'s SELECT projection, once per row,\n  evaluated against the f32 blob already materialised in the\n  staging row. No Rust-side bit math; no double scan of the\n  source blob.\n- **Atomicity.** `apply_one` wraps the whole SQL blob in\n  `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT` and `ROLLBACK`s on any error\n  (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`). If any sub-step\n  fails, the migration is rolled back, `PRAGMA user_version`\n  stays at the previous value, and the next open re-attempts\n  the migration cleanly. The staging + sentinel tables are part\n  of the same transaction and are dropped on rollback alongside\n  the would-be new `vector_default`.\n- **Fail-fast on unknown kinds.** Sub-step 0 above creates a\n  `_vec0_migration_assertion(check_passes INTEGER NOT NULL\n  CHECK(check_passes = 1))` sentinel table and INSERTs the\n  result of an `EXISTS` probe against the locked vocabulary\n  (incl. `doc`). If any row in `_fathomdb_vector_rows` has a\n  `kind` outside `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo,\n  doc}`, the probe evaluates to 0, the CHECK constraint fires\n  `SQLITE_CONSTRAINT` at INSERT time, and `apply_one` rolls\n  back the whole step. CHECK constraints on regular SQL tables\n  are a built-in SQLite primitive\n  (https://www.sqlite.org/lang_createtable.html#check_constraints);\n  no extension and no trigger required. (Alternative shapes\n  considered: a single-statement CTE with a forced UNIQUE\n  violation, or a Rust-side preflight in `open_with_migrations`\n  before `migrate_with_event_sink`. Neither is necessary here\n  because `apply_one` calls `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)`\n  — multi-statement semantics, re-verified at\n  `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:276` — so the preflight can be a\n  prefix statement in the same SQL string.) This is what\n  encodes the D3 \"writer error on unknown kind\" rule at\n  migration time; the writer enforces it independently at\n  steady-state write time via `resolve_source_type` in D3 / D5.\n- **NOT NULL enforcement at write time.** vec0 metadata columns\n  do not have a declarative `NOT NULL` constraint in the\n  sqlite-vec DDL surface\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);\n  non-nullability is contract-enforced by the migration and by\n  the D5/D7 writers. Pack 1 writers always supply all five\n  metadata columns; the migration always supplies them (the\n  CASE's ELSE branch is `'article'`, not NULL, and the\n  sub-step 0 preflight has already proven the ELSE branch is\n  unreachable for in-tree corpora). No row can land with a NULL.\n\nMigration cost: dominated by two sequential scans of the\nexisting 3 GB f32 corpus on the 1 M-row fixture — one for the\nstaging `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 1) and one for the\nrepopulation `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 3). The\n`vec_quantize_binary` work is a sign-bit fold per coordinate,\nnegligible relative to the I/O. The working budget remains the\n60-90 s estimate from ADR § 4. The migration **does not** re-run\nthe embedder, so the AC-013 562 s seed time\n(`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`)\nis **not** a comparable baseline — that figure includes embedder\nwork this migration avoids by construction. A concrete\nmeasurement lands in P1-IMPL's GREEN gate.\n\nIdempotence: `PRAGMA user_version` already guards re-entry\n(`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:234`, `:277`). On the second open\nthe migration step is skipped because `migration.step_id <=\nbefore`, and `vector_default` keeps the rows from the first\npass.\n\n### Rejected alternative — repopulate via `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n\nThe fix-1 draft of D4 proposed driving repopulation through\n`Engine::rebuild_vec0` (`lib.rs:1947`), which calls\n`run_rebuild` -> `rebuild_shadow_state` with `RebuildKind::Vec0`\n(`lib.rs:2234-2289`). Codex fix-1 review (finding 1,\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`)\ncorrectly flagged that this path:\n\n- Is asynchronous. `rebuild_shadow_state` only truncates vec0\n  state and resets the projection cursor; the actual\n  re-derivation runs on the projection scheduler. The test at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`\n  observes `rebuild_vec0` returns immediately and polls\n  `projection_status_for_test` to wait for the async drain.\n- Re-runs the embedder. The projection scheduler's\n  `run_projection_job` calls `embedder.embed(&job.body)` at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2528-2557` for\n  every row it re-derives.\n- Is therefore not equivalent to copying the existing f32\n  blobs: it would multiply the migration cost by the embedder\n  work the migration is specifically designed to avoid, and it\n  would leak a window in which `vector_default` is empty before\n  the async drain catches up.\n\nThe staged-copy migration above replaces this path entirely.\n`rebuild_vec0` remains as it is in tree for the operator-driven\n\"rebuild from canonical\" tool; Pack 1's migration does not call\nit.\n\n## D5 — Writer transaction shape\n\nThe writer site is `commit_projection_outcomes` at\n`lib.rs:2845-2853`. The double-write lands in the **same**\n`tx.execute` sequence between the existing\n`_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert and the existing\n`record_projection_terminal` call. No extra commit; no extra\nlock; no extra connection.\n\n**Decision: compute `vec_quantize_binary` inside the SQL\nstatement (single `INSERT` per row), not in Rust ahead of bind.**\n\nThe rewritten statement:\n\n```rust\ntx.execute(\n    \"INSERT OR IGNORE INTO vector_default(\n        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n)?;\n```\n\nJustification (one paragraph):\n\nThe SQL-side shape keeps the f32 blob single-bound (one rusqlite\n`Vec<u8>` allocation, one bind), lets sqlite-vec compute the\nbit-vector against its own internal blob layout (which is what\nthe Pack 2 reader will also see), and avoids pulling a Rust-side\n`vec_quantize_binary` dependency or re-implementing the sign-bit\nfold in the engine crate. The \"double-evaluation\" concern (vec0\nmaterialising `?2` twice) is a non-issue because the binary\nquantization is a single sequential sign-bit pass over the same\nin-memory blob — both passes operate on the same bound parameter\nand the SQLite parameter store does not copy. The Rust-side\nalternative would (a) require either linking against sqlite-vec's\nC symbols from Rust or shipping a hand-rolled sign-fold, (b)\ndouble the f32 footprint at bind time, and (c) couple the engine\ncrate to the on-the-wire bit format which is sqlite-vec's\ninternal concern. SQL-side is the cleaner contract surface.\n\n## D6 — `vec_quantize_binary()` contract validation plan\n\nThe Pack 1 RED test is a round-trip:\n\n1. Build a known f32 vector `v` of length `<dim>` whose sign\n   pattern is hand-checkable.\n2. Insert via the writer path.\n3. Assert `vec_distance_hamming(embedding_bin, vec_quantize_binary(vec_f32(v))) = 0`.\n\nSpecified fixture (deterministic, no normalisation involved):\n\n```\ndim = 768.\nv[i] = +1.0 for i in 0..384, -1.0 for i in 384..768.\n```\n\nExpected `embedding_bin`: 384 set bits in the leading half, 384\nclear bits in the trailing half. Popcount = 384. The exact bit\nordering (LSB-first within each byte vs MSB-first) is an\nsqlite-vec internal contract; the round-trip via\n`vec_quantize_binary` guarantees both writer and reader see the\nsame packing, which is the only invariant the engine relies on.\n`vec_distance_hamming` against the same vector binarised the same\nway must be 0.\n\nOne fixture is sufficient. The previously-drafted secondary\n\"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed (its claim that\n`normalise([1,-1,1,-1,...])` and the half/half vector share\n\"identical sign patterns at every coordinate\" is wrong — one is\nhalf-positive/half-negative, the other alternates — see codex\nverdict finding 3). If P1-IMPL wants a second fixture for\ndefence-in-depth, the recommended shape is a vector that is +1\non every fourth coordinate and -1 elsewhere\n(`v3[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0` for dim=768): popcount\nof the quantization is exactly 192 set bits, trivially\nhand-checked, and clearly distinct from the half/half fixture's\npopcount of 384.\n\nValidation status: **empirical validation deferred to P1-IMPL's\nRED test.** A one-shot `sqlite3` confirmation against a temp DB\nwith `sqlite-vec` loaded was considered for this memo but\nrejected because (a) the Rust crate is the binding the writer\nactually uses and the sqlite3 CLI binding is a separate code\npath, (b) P1-IMPL's RED test exercises the engine writer\nend-to-end which is the only contract that matters, and (c) the\nbinary-quant guide\n(https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)\nalready documents the round-trip shape and `vec_distance_hamming`\nbehaviour. If the RED test surfaces a contract surprise (signed\nzero, NaN, byte-order), that is HITL escalation territory per\nthe ADR § 6 / \"vec_quantize_binary() input expectations\" — not\nsomething this design memo can resolve in advance.\n\nOpen-item linkage: the ADR § 6 third bullet calls out the\nfixture's \"atypically friendly\" sign-pattern concentration (mass\non 6 of 768 coordinates per `tests/perf_gates.rs:317`). That is a\nrecall-headroom concern for Pack 2, not a contract concern for\nPack 1. Pack 1's RED test is correctness, not recall.\n\n## D7 — Second writer site (test-only)\n\nConfirmed. The test-only helper at\n`Engine::write_vector_for_test` (`lib.rs:1806-1845`) is a second\ningest path that inserts into `vector_default` (line 1838). Pack 1\nmust update this site in lockstep with `commit_projection_outcomes`\nor it will violate the NOT NULL contract on `embedding_bin` /\n`source_type` / `kind` / `created_at` and break every test that\ngoes through `write_vector_for_test`.\n\nThe rewritten test helper insert is structurally identical to D5:\n\n```rust\ntx.execute(\n    \"INSERT INTO vector_default(\n        rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at\n     ) VALUES(?1, ?2, vec_quantize_binary(?2), ?3, ?4, ?5)\",\n    params![cursor, blob, resolve_source_type(kind)?, kind, now_unix],\n)?;\n```\n\nPack 1 implementation MUST touch both:\n\n- `lib.rs:1832-1841` (test helper writer; the\n  `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert at :1832-1836 also needs the\n  same `kind` value flow as `commit_projection_outcomes`).\n- `lib.rs:2845-2852` (production writer; D5 site).\n\nNo other writer site touches `vector_default`. The delete sites\n(`lib.rs:2177`, `:2265`) are unaffected — they target the row by\nrowid and the column changes are append-only at the schema level.\nThe writer-loop pins at `:2174`, `:2181`, `:2242` are not touched\n(they DELETE-by-rowid or operate on the shadow `_fathomdb_vector_rows`\ntable, not on the metadata columns being added).\n\n## D8 — Reader-path NO-OP guarantee\n\nThe Pack 2 reader rewrite is out of scope. The Pack 1 question is:\ndoes the **existing** reader at `read_search_in_tx`\n(`lib.rs:2317-2323`) keep working over the migrated schema?\n\nThe existing query is:\n\n```sql\nSELECT rowid FROM vector_default\nWHERE embedding MATCH vec_f32(?1)\nORDER BY distance\nLIMIT 10\n```\n\n**Decision: confirmed no-op. The existing reader continues to\nreturn identical results post-migration.**\n\nReasoning:\n\n- The `embedding` column is **retained** (ADR § 2.1 \"the f32\n  `embedding` column is retained\"). Its declared type\n  `float[<dim>]` is unchanged.\n- vec0's MATCH semantics dispatch on the column referenced in the\n  predicate; adding sibling vector columns\n  (`embedding_bin bit[<dim>]`) and metadata columns\n  (`source_type`, `kind`, `created_at`) does not alter the\n  semantics of `embedding MATCH vec_f32(?)`.\n- The metadata + partition-key release blog\n  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html)\n  demonstrates a vec0 declaration with `partition key` + plain\n  metadata columns + the vector column, queried by the vector\n  predicate alone; the additional columns are filterable via\n  `WHERE` but do not become mandatory in the query shape.\n- The Pack 1 migration preserves the `rowid <-> write_cursor`\n  identity by JOIN-ing `vector_default.rowid` into the staging\n  table (D4 sub-step 1: `SELECT v.rowid, v.embedding, r.kind\n  FROM vector_default v JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid\n  = v.rowid`) and then repopulating the recreated\n  `vector_default` with the same staged rowids (D4 sub-step 3:\n  `INSERT INTO vector_default(rowid, ...) SELECT s.rowid, ...\n  FROM _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 s`); the writer-loop\n  pins at `lib.rs:2174-2175`, `:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265` continue\n  to hold.\n\nAC-013 latency therefore stays at 2048 / 2327 ms post-Pack 1\n(matches the ADR § 4 / handoff § 1 stated contract). AC-019\nstays at its existing bound. AC-012 / AC-017 / AC-018 / AC-020\nare untouched because they do not query `vector_default`.\n\n## Open escalations\n\nNone. All eight decisions resolved against repo + cited external\ndocs. The pre-existing open items in the ADR § 6 (\"final numeric\nbudgets\", \"K-value selection\", \"fixture-friendliness for recall\")\nare Pack 2 concerns and are not affected by Pack 1.\n\n## Fix-1 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`.\n\n- **Fix 1.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D3 no longer extends\n  the HITL-locked 6-value `source_type` vocabulary. The\n  synthetic AC-013 fixture kind `\"doc\"` is now coerced at the\n  writer to `source_type = \"article\"`. The locked vocabulary\n  `{email, article, paper, meeting, note, todo}` holds exactly;\n  no HITL re-open required. Mapping table + rationale + reject\n  list updated in D3.\n- **Fix 1.2 (verdict finding 2, high).** D4 migration rewritten\n  to use the engine's real migration framework:\n  `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at `lib.rs:1238`, gated by\n  `PRAGMA user_version`. The vec0 rebuild is `DROP TABLE` +\n  `CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE` under the same name (sqlite-vec 0.1.7\n  has no `ALTER TABLE RENAME` support; that lands in\n  `v0.1.10-alpha.2`). (Repopulation shape later replaced by\n  the fix-2 staged copy; see Fix-2 changelog below.)\n- **Fix 1.3 (verdict finding 3, medium).** D6 secondary\n  \"normalised alternating-sign\" fixture is removed. The\n  half/half popcount-384 fixture remains as the sole RED-test\n  fixture; an optional defence-in-depth fixture\n  (`v[i] = +1.0 if i % 4 == 0 else -1.0`, popcount = 192) is\n  recorded for P1-IMPL's discretion.\n\n## Fix-2 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`\n(one new high finding on D4's repopulation semantics).\n\n- **Fix 2.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D4 repopulation no\n  longer routes through `Engine::rebuild_vec0` /\n  `rebuild_shadow_state` (`RebuildKind::Vec0`). Verified against\n  the actual code: `run_projection_job` at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2523-2557` calls\n  `embedder.embed(&job.body)` per row, and the rebuild test at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`\n  locks in async drain semantics — both contradict the fix-1\n  claim that repopulation is synchronous and avoids the\n  embedder. D4 is replaced with a single SQL migration step\n  executed under `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`,\n  re-verified): (1) stage existing `vector_default` rows\n  JOIN-ed with `_fathomdb_vector_rows.kind` into a regular\n  staging table, (2) `DROP TABLE vector_default` + recreate\n  with the Pack 1 schema, (3) `INSERT ... SELECT` from staging\n  with `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side and a CASE expression\n  rendering the D3 `kind -> source_type` map, (4) drop the\n  staging table. Properties recorded explicitly: synchronous,\n  no embedder rerun, atomic under `BEGIN IMMEDIATE`/`COMMIT`,\n  `vec_quantize_binary` SQL-side once per row. Cost citation\n  updated: the AC-013 562 s seed figure is no longer cited as\n  a baseline because it includes embedder work this migration\n  avoids; budget remains the 60-90 s ADR § 4 estimate. A\n  \"Rejected alternative\" subsection added under D4 explaining\n  why `rebuild_vec0` is not used.\n- **Fix 2.2 (consequence).** D4 SQL-only migration shape is\n  justified against the actual `Migration { step_id: u32, sql:\n  &'static str }` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`\n  (re-verified) — pure SQL, no Rust callback extension point.\n  CASE WHEN is the migration-time mirror of the D3 helper\n  `resolve_source_type`; P1-IMPL is directed to add a\n  co-located drift-detection assertion.\n\n## Fix-3 changelog\n\nAddresses codex BLOCK verdict at\n`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-2-review-20260527T135041Z.md`\n(one high, one medium, one low — all localized to D4 internal\nconsistency and one stale D8 citation).\n\n- **Fix 3.1 (verdict finding 1, high).** D4's \"unknown kind =\n  error\" rule no longer relies on the unsupported `ELSE NULL` +\n  vec0 NOT NULL combination. The migration SQL now prefixes the\n  staged-copy with a real fail-fast preflight: a\n  `_vec0_migration_assertion(check_passes INTEGER NOT NULL\n  CHECK(check_passes = 1))` sentinel table whose INSERT computes\n  `CASE WHEN EXISTS(... kind NOT IN locked-vocab ...) THEN 0\n  ELSE 1 END`. An unknown kind drives `check_passes = 0`, the\n  CHECK constraint fires `SQLITE_CONSTRAINT` at INSERT time, and\n  `apply_one`'s ROLLBACK undoes the whole step (sentinel table\n  included). The CHECK primitive is vanilla SQLite (cited:\n  https://www.sqlite.org/lang_createtable.html#check_constraints);\n  no extension, no trigger required. Multi-statement viability\n  re-verified empirically against `apply_one` at\n  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`, which\n  calls `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)` (line 276) — batch\n  semantics, so the preflight can be a prefix statement in the\n  same SQL string. The repopulating CASE keeps `ELSE 'article'`\n  (defence-in-depth past the assertion; justified inline in D4).\n- **Fix 3.2 (verdict finding 2, medium).** D4 no longer claims\n  a Rust-rendered `<now>` literal or any migration-build-time\n  timestamp construction. The `created_at` column is filled by\n  `strftime('%s','now')` evaluated at INSERT time inside the\n  migration SQL. The uniform-timestamp guarantee is per INSERT\n  statement: SQLite's date/time functions return the same value\n  across all rows in a single statement when no varying\n  arguments are passed (cited:\n  https://www.sqlite.org/lang_datefunc.html). The stale\n  `open_with_migrations` (`lib.rs:1119`) anchor is removed from\n  D4 — no Rust path is involved in the timestamp.\n- **Fix 3.3 (verdict finding 3, low).** D8's stale `INSERT INTO\n  vector_default_v2 ... SELECT v.rowid` proof point (left over\n  from the pre-fix-2 sibling-table draft) is replaced with the\n  staged-copy proof: rowid is the explicit JOIN key in the\n  staging INSERT (`SELECT v.rowid, ... FROM vector_default v\n  JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid = v.rowid`), and the\n  recreated `vector_default` receives the same staged rowid in\n  the repopulation INSERT. Conclusion (rowid <-> write_cursor\n  identity preserved; writer-loop pins at `lib.rs:2174-2175`,\n  `:2177`, `:2181`, `:2265` continue to hold) is unchanged.\n","numLines":761,"startLine":1,"totalLines":761}}}
